1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,171
During World War II, the Navy made sure that all of its new recruits either knew how to swim or learned how,

2
00:00:07,280 --> 00:00:13,891
the idea being, of course, that the ability to swim might someday save the sailors' life at sea.

3
00:00:14,400 --> 00:00:17,731
Non-swimming recruits were put into swimming classes.

4
00:00:17,920 --> 00:00:21,090
I watched a number of these training experiences.

5
00:00:21,361 --> 00:00:28,771
In a superficial sort of way, it was amusing to see young, healthy men terrified by a few feet of water.

6
00:00:29,120 --> 00:00:34,530
One of the exercises, I recall, required the new sailor to jump, not dive,

7
00:00:34,560 --> 00:00:38,851
from a board six feet in the air into eight or more feet of water,

8
00:00:38,960 --> 00:00:42,210
while a half-dozen expert swimmers stood by.

9
00:00:42,880 --> 00:00:45,971
In a deeper sense, it was a sad sight.

10
00:00:46,160 --> 00:00:49,331
The fear those young men displayed was real.

11
00:00:49,600 --> 00:00:55,731
Yet all that stood between them and the defeat of that fear was one drop into the water below.

12
00:00:56,081 --> 00:01:01,571
On more than one occasion, I saw young men accidentally pushed off the board.

13
00:01:01,680 --> 00:01:02,451
The result?

14
00:01:02,641 --> 00:01:04,131
Fear defeated.

15
00:01:04,641 --> 00:01:10,691
This incident, familiar to thousands of former Navy men, illustrates just one point.

16
00:01:11,040 --> 00:01:12,930
Action cures fear.

17
00:01:13,200 --> 00:01:17,650
Indecision, postponement, on the other hand, fertilize fear.

18
00:01:18,241 --> 00:01:21,891
Jot that down in your success rule book right now.

19
00:01:22,160 --> 00:01:24,051
Action cures fear.

20
00:01:24,801 --> 00:01:26,771
Action does cure fear.

